xxl.core.cursors.filters
Class WhileRemover<E>

java.lang.Object
  xxl.core.cursors.SecureDecoratorCursor<E>
      xxl.core.cursors.filters.Remover<E>
          xxl.core.cursors.filters.WhileRemover<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of the elements returned by this iteration.
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.util.Iterator<E>, Cursor<E>
public class WhileRemover<E>
extends Remover<E>

A while-remover removes the elements of an input cursor with the help of a user defined predicate (or boolean function). It removes the elements as long as the result of the user defined, unary predicate applied to the next element of the input cursor is true. An instance of a while-remover is created as follows: 

   super(new WhileTaker<E>(iterator, predicate));
So simply a new while-taker is created that selects the elements with the help of the given predicate and this instance of a while-taker is used as the input cursor of a remover.

Note: If the input iteration is given by an object of the class Iterator, i.e., it does not support the peek operation, it is internally wrapped to a cursor. If a boolean function is specified in a constructor it is also internally wrapped to a predicate.

See Also:
Iterator, Cursor, Remover, WhileTaker

Constructor Detail

WhileRemover

public WhileRemover(java.util.Iterator<E> iterator,
                    Predicate<? super E> predicate)
Creates a new while-remover backed on an iteration and an unary predicate applied on the iteration's elements. The iteration's elements will be removed from the underlying data structure as long as the specified predicate returns true.

The implementation of this constructor is as follows: 

   super(new WhileTaker<E>(iterator, predicate));
So a while-taker is created that selects the elements with the help of the given predicate, and this instance of a while-taker is used as the input for a remover.

Parameters:
iterator - the input iteration the elements will be removed from as long as the specified predicate applied on the current element returns true.
predicate - the unary predicate used to select the elements of the input iteration.

WhileRemover

public WhileRemover(java.util.Iterator<E> iterator,
                    Function<? super E,java.lang.Boolean> function)
Creates a new while-remover backed on an iteration and an unary boolean function applied on the iteration's elements. The iteration's elements will be removed from the underlying data structure as long as the specified function returns Boolean.TRUE.

Parameters:
iterator - the input iteration the elements will be removed from as long as the specified predicate applied on the current element returns true.
function - the unary boolean function used to select the elements of the input iteration.
